# Supabase Realtime signaling for Trystero (optional override).
#
# The project URL + publishable key are already baked into src/config.js
# as defaults, so the game works without a .env file. Set these only to
# point a build at a DIFFERENT Supabase project (e.g. staging) without
# touching the source. Blank them out to fall back to the public relays.
#
# Only the WebRTC handshake crosses Supabase; once peers link up, all
# gameplay data flows directly peer-to-peer.
#
# Where to find these: Supabase dashboard -> Project Settings -> API.
#   - VITE_SUPABASE_URL = "Project URL", the bare origin, NO "/rest/v1/"
#                         (e.g. https://xxxx.supabase.co)
#   - VITE_SUPABASE_KEY = the "sb_publishable_..." key (safe to ship in the
#                         client; the current replacement for the anon key)
#
# Copy this file to `.env` and fill in your project's values.
VITE_SUPABASE_URL=
VITE_SUPABASE_KEY=

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TURN server (optional but STRONGLY recommended for cross-network play).
#
# Every transport above is only SIGNALING — the actual match is a direct
# WebRTC connection between the two browsers. Trystero ships public STUN
# servers, which work on most home networks. But when both players are behind
# strict NAT/firewalls (symmetric NAT, blocked UDP, many mobile carriers,
# corporate/campus Wi-Fi), STUN can't connect them and the match fails on
# EVERY transport at once — Supabase, Nostr, torrent and MQTT alike, because
# they share the same WebRTC layer. That is the usual cause of "nothing
# connects and it makes no sense".
#
# A TURN server relays the connection (over TCP/443) as a last resort and gets
# through almost anything. Open the game with ?netdebug to see the built-in
# ICE self-check tell you whether you actually need one.
#
# Get free/cheap TURN from Metered (metered.ca — free tier), Cloudflare
# Realtime TURN, Twilio, or self-host coturn. Then:
#   VITE_TURN_URL  = comma-separated TURN urls (include a TCP/443 one), e.g.
#                    turn:xxxx.relay.metered.ca:443,turns:xxxx.relay.metered.ca:443?transport=tcp
#   VITE_TURN_USER = TURN username
#   VITE_TURN_CRED = TURN credential / password
VITE_TURN_URL=
VITE_TURN_USER=
VITE_TURN_CRED=
